  "doc_id": "45876",
  "text": "However, between individuals and society lies the problem of language, the interpretation of propositional statements and performativity, and the complexities in that discussion for the investigation of belief. As noted above, many studies \"reveal how believers convince themselves that their beliefs are true,\" which prompted Lindholm to discuss the two camps of justification and verification ( [CITATION_1] , p. 341). In part, the observed methods of justification and verification, as well as the varieties of discourse, present a range of ways by which social institutions and structures influence individual thought, value, and meaning-making processes. Tanya Luhrmann's work on \"interpretive drift\" (in the case of modern witchcraft in England) and the \"imagination\" (among evangelical Christians in the U.S.) contributes to the discussion about this process. Jonathan Mair's proposal of \"cultures of belief\" also configures within this dynamic by which persons, as historically-situated beings, develop and justify their beliefs and propositional attitudes as true through practice.",
